- Writing short news items on treaties statuses for the daily Tax News Service;
- Updating, proofreading, and processing (formatting and converting into XML) international tax treaties information for their publication on the IBFD Tax Research Platform;
- Managing internal administrative documentation and procedures.

My responsibilities involved a complex range of demands, mostly related to the patients' (PLWHA - People Living with HIV/AIDS) low adherence to treatment, which was generally associated with social issues (e.g. poor access to public services, unemployment, low educational level, cognitive issues, socioeconomic difficulties, mental illness, homelessness, and/or abuse of alcohol and/or other drugs). My tasks included:

- Social follow-up assistance through interviews with the patients and their relatives for orientation and clarification on available social services, both internal and external to the Hospital;
- Contact with other members of the professional healthcare team, always pointing to an interdisciplinary approach;
- Contact with the external social support network, including home and institutional visits;
- Technical and administrative tasks;
- Participation in workshops and seminars.

During this internship, I also had the opportunity to elaborate and implement an intervention project related to the post-discharge social follow-up of HIV/AIDS patients, aiming to reinforce the integrality of healthcare assistance and to contribute to the strengthening of treatment adherence, avoiding hospital readmissions. This experience was also the subject of my graduate dissertation – "The Social Worker’s Work with People Living with HIV/AIDS in the Context of High Complexity and the Integrality of Healthcare" –, which received an indication from the Examination Board to publish it in book form.

The Undergraduate Student Support Nucleus (NAE), linked to the Program of Support to the Graduation - Service of Orientation to the Learning Process/UFRGS, offers assistance to students and graduates, professors, technicians, and partners of the university (UFRGS).
During this scholarship, I worked directly with psychologists and pedagogues, from whom I learned several things about academic and career counselling, which made the experience even more rewarding. I was also able to participate as an assistant in the seminars regarding support and orientation to students with academic difficulties, wherein students shared their experiences, concerns, and anxieties about the learning process, academic requirements, the struggle of choosing a career, social interaction issues, etc.

Duties and responsibilities:

- Monitoring activities in the "Graduation Support Project": assistance in the execution of seminars regarding the academic and professional lives of students, aiming to offer support and orientation;
- Customer service;
- Technical and administrative tasks.

The "InterSossego Project", linked to the Extension and Research Program on "Urban Health, Environment, and Inequalities"/UFRGS, is an interdisciplinary and intersectoral community extension activity, carried out in partnership amongst UFRGS (university), UBS Santa Cecília/HCPA (basic healthcare service), CRAS/Centre (Social Work Reference Centre) and the Vila Sossego community (a subnormal urban agglomeration), aiming to local social development. 
This experience provided me with differentiated knowledge through interdisciplinary work. Combining different perspectives, from different fields of expertise, it allowed me to go beyond theoretical knowledge, enabling constructive exchanges with the community and the project members. Moreover, I have improved my communication and research capabilities, having advanced my knowledge of urban health.

Duties and responsibilities:

- Team meetings with the local social and healthcare network to discuss the community's reality, seeking to tackle its social issues;
- Interaction with the community through cultural and socio-pedagogical activities;
- Research and elaboration of projects and academic works related to urban health (one of our projects was published and awarded during the 16th "Extension Hall", at UFRGS, in October of 2015: "Integrality and Intersectoriality - Multiprofessional Work in the Vila Sossego Community").

The Ombudsman of the Municipal Health Department of Porto Alegre manages the health system for the city's population (around 1.5 million people), where I was responsible for receiving, registering, and categorising the citizens' demands in person, assisting them by elucidating the city's health and social services. Beyond developing even further my communication and writing skills, I also acquired a remarkable knowledge regarding the management of the public health system: SUS - Sistema Único de Saúde (Brazilian Unified National Health System). 

Duties and responsibilities:

- Interviews with the citizens for orientation and clarification on municipal health and social services;
- Registration and categorisation of demands, addressing them to the responsible sectors;
- Internal data control;
- Preparation of information material and monthly management reports;
- Technical and administrative activities.

The Support House offers accommodation for children and teenagers (from 0 to 18 years of age) who are being treated in the Oncology, Hematology, General Pediatrics, and/or Transplants Services of the Hospital. It is a house where patients, along with their relatives, can sleep, eat, and rest, as if it was their own home. The aim is to offer accommodation to people who come from the countryside (or from other states of Brazil) to do their treatments; people who lack resources and cannot afford a place to stay.
This internship helped me to develop many competencies, as my self-knowledge, my capacity for interpersonal relationships, my communication skills, and strengthened my decision-making skills, advancing my autonomy as a Social Work professional. It was the first opportunity I had to interview patients by myself, and it was also my first contact with such sensitive matters, dealing with diseases and the issue of death, which was very challenging, I must say, especially when it involved children. This experience helped me to cope with the deep emotional situations that often occur within a healthcare setting. I had to learn how to manage my emotions and, at the same time, how to handle patients' (and their family members) emotions.

Duties and responsibilities:

- Social follow-up, conducting interviews with the patients and their relatives;
- Group meetings with the relatives housed, aiming to give emotional support and to orientate about social services offered by the Hospital and other institutions;
- Participation in cultural, playful, and pedagogical activities, such as workshops and projects, for the children and teenagers housed;
- Technical and administrative activities.

- Customer service;
- Internal data control;
- Preparation of management reports;
- Technical and administrative activities;
- Organization of graduation ceremonies.

- Doing pre-opening preparations, by cleaning and organising the dining areas;
- Taking customer orders and serving food and beverages;
- Sporadically bartending.
